\f0\b\fs40 \cf0 Match Settings of the\

\f1\b0\fs32 \
Matches are evaluated according to two parameters called "primability" and "stability." They both measure how well the primer matches the target site, but the former emphasizes matches at the 3' end, and the latter places more weight on runs of consecutive matches. You can adjust how these parameters are calculated by changing the settings. Here is what the values {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.macworld.com"}}{\fldrslt mean}}:\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 \
Degenerate Code Scores\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 The parameters are computed by summing the contributions from each base position. The contributions are the "degenerate code scores" (with the primer base being shown on the vertical axis and the target base on the horizontal) multiplied by a weighting factor.\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 \
Run Weights\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 The first value is applied to single matches surrounded by mismatches; the second to runs of two matches, and so on. Note that the numbers increase with the length of run. These quantities are used to compute the "stability" of a match. Normally, you will want longer runs of matches to count more toward the stability.\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 \
Where do the default numbers come from?\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 I just made them up. Well ... not quite. They actually come from a great deal of trial and error in which I kept tinkering with the values until they successfully predicted the great majority of PCR experiments run in my lab. If you find values that work better for you, be sure to hit the "Save As Defaults" button so that 
\i \cf3 Amplify
\i0 \cf0  will use your values in the future.\
\
\

\f0\b\fs40 Target Sequence\

\f1\b0\fs32 \
This window holds the target sequence for amplification. You can add a sequence to by copying and pasting, or else by opening a text file.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Sequence headers\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 Some sequence files come with a preamble or header before the actual sequence begins. Amplify assumes that there is a specific string that separates the header from the rest of the sequence. You can set this header string as whatever you like in the "Preferences" dialog. For example, a delimiter string might be "End Header" or "..". Having a sequence header is optional.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Styled text\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf3 Amplify\cf0  allows you to mark specified parts of your target by changing the color or setting the text as boldface or italicization. This feature is handy for marking areas of interest. These styles have no effect on the amplification. You are also free to use upper or lower case letters. \
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Allowable characters\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 The actual sequence part of the text (i.e., the text following any sequence header) must consist of the letters A, T, C, G or N (or a, t, c, g or n). Any other characters will be removed. Note that other IUB codes are allowed in the primer specifications but not in the target sequence.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Pattern Finding\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf3 Amplify\cf0  provides a powerful pattern finder for use in working with the target sequence. Simply select it from under the "Edit" menu or press command-F. You can use any of the IUB codes in your search pattern and also specify an additional number of allowable mismatches. The "Find Next" commands searches for the most recent pattern, but starts from the selection instead of the start. \
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Sequence formatting\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 When you hit the "Format Sequence" button, Amplify identifies any sequence header and strips out any disallowed characters in the sequence. The style information is protected. This formatting is also done if necessary during an amplification.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Inversion\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 You can invert any selected portion of the target sequence by hitting the "Invert" button or by selecting "Invert Selection" under the Edit menu. Note that \cf3 Amplify\cf0  remembers the text style (color, etc.) of each character during the inversion.\
\
\
\

\f0\b\fs40 Preferences\

\f1\b0\fs32 \
Any changes you make to the Preferences are active after you hit the Okay button. If you hit "Save As Defaults" those changes will also be available next time you run \cf3 Amplify\cf0 . If you want to restore the original settings, hit the "Factory Settings" button.\
\
Note that the size and position of the windows will also be preserved when you hit the "Save As Defaults" button provided you have this option checked.\
\

\f0\b\fs40 Primer List\

\f1\b0\fs32 \
You will need a list of your available primers from which to select one or more to use in a particular amplification. To select a primer for use, click on the checkbox in the leftmost column.  All checked primers will be used when you perform an amplification by selecting "Amplify" under the PCR menu.\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2  \
Constructing a primer list\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf3 Amplify 3\cf0  can use primer lists made with earlier versions provided you used the Tab character to separate fields. You can also build or modify your list within \cf3 Amplify\cf0  by typing or pasting in the information. You can add a new row to the bottom of the list by clicking in last cell and hitting the Tab key. Be sure to save the list after you make your changes.\
\
It is also easy to construct your primer list with another application, such as a word processor or spreadsheet program. The output must be a TEXT file where each line specifies a single primer starting with the sequence followed by a short name and optional notes. Fields are separated by Tab characters.\
\
To reverse the sequence, select the sequence you want to invert and pick "Invert Selection" from the Edit menu.\
