\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 The primer sequence\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
You can enter the sequence using any of the standard IUB base codes. Upper and lower case are ignored. Styled text is not supported in the primer list.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Searching and sorting\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
You can sort your primer list according to any column by clicking on the header of that column. Click the header again to sort it in reverse order. Search for any text in the primer list by selecting "Find ..." from the Edit menu or hitting command-F.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Primer information\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
Select a primer by clicking on its sequence, name or notes, then click on "Primer Info" to see various pieces of information about that primer's sequence. If it has a potential to self-dimerize, the hypothetical alignment will also be shown. \
\

\f0\b\fs40 Define Target Sequence\

\f1\b0\fs32 \
You can tell \cf3 Amplify\cf0  to use your entire target sequence (the default) or any subset. If you already have the desired subset selected in the target sequence window, just check the "Use Selection" box to have the corresponding numbers put into the boxes for you.\
\
Amplify will treat your target sequence as either linear or circular according to your choice. If you choose circular, then some additional fragments might show up on your amplification map.  These additional ones will appear as interrupted lines and have arrowheads at the left and right ends to indicate that they can be thought of as continuing around a circle.\

\f0\b\fs40 Primer Dimers\

\f1\b0\fs32 \
Some primers have the potential to pair up in such a way that they can use each other as templates for DNA synthesis. For example, two primers might line up this way:\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri-19445

\f3 \cf0 5' GTCGGCTACTCCTTGCGTCG 3'  \
                  |||||\
               3' GCAGCCCTGGTGGAATACAA 5'  
\f1 \
\
This process prevents the primers from functioning properly in your reaction. Worse yet, the resulting small fragments can form a particularly nasty kind of contaminant in your lab, poisoning future reactions that use either of these two primers.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri-19445
\cf3 Amplify\cf0  can show you pairs that it considers having some potential for dimer formation. Then you can decide for yourself whether the combination is dangerous to your reaction.\
\
You can adjust the parameters and stringency used to determine which dimers are flagged by changing the settings in\cf3  Amplify\cf0 's Preferences dialog.\
\

\f0\b\fs40 PCR Settings\

\f1\b0\fs32 \

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Maximum Effective Primer Length\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 You can still use primers longer than this, but the excess sequence at the 5' end will be ignored.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Primability and Stability cutoffs\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
Indicate the lowest parameter values, expressed as a percent of the maximum for a given primer, for which you want \cf3 Amplify\cf0  to show you matches. If you set them too low, your map will be cluttered with irrelevant matches. Too high, and you might miss some matches that actually function in the PCR. The default values are ones I've found to be about optimal, at least for my lab.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Default Target (linear or circular)\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
You can always decide whether you want your target sequence to be treated as linear or circular when you perform the amplification. However, this setting tells \cf3 Amplify\cf0  which form you want to consider as the default.\
\

\f0\b\fs40 Tm Calculations\

\f1\b0\fs32 \
Melting temperatures for primers are calculated by the "nearest neighbor" method. This method, as well as the entropy and enthalpy values, come from the "Primer" program of the Eric Lander lab, and are used here with permission from the authors.\
\

\f0\b\fs40 Primer Dimer calculation parameters\

\f1\b0\fs32 \
Amplify flags potential primer-dimer combinations if (1) the region of overlap is at least as large as the number specified, and (2) the "quality" of the match within the overlap is greater than a cutoff value set by the Stringency slider on this panel.\
\
The "quality" is the sum of the numbers for in the shown matrix for each base pair. You can set the numbers to be whatever you like. The defaults were computed as A + wG \'96 M, where A is the probability of an A-T pair, G is the probability of a G-C pair, and M is the probability of a mismatch. The weighting factor, w, gives extra weight to G-C pairs. I used w = 1.5 in arriving at the default values.\
\
These criteria seem to work well in practice in identifying potential dimer-forming pairs, but they are not based on any theory. Feel free to try other values, and please let me know if you find a set that works better than the defaults.\

\f0\b\fs40 General Preferences\

\fs28 \cf2 \
Save Window Positions\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
When this box is checked, \cf3 Amplify\cf0  will remember the positions and sizes of the various windows and save them in your Prefs file when you hit the "Save As Defaults" button. Most users will want to take advantage of this feature so that all of \cf3 Amplify\cf0 's windows will fit well on the screen.  Then, the next time you run the program, your windows will be where you expect them.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Automatically load primer file\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
When this box is checked, \cf3 Amplify\cf0  will find and load your standard primer list. A good practice is to keep all your available primers in one list, and set that file to be loaded automatically.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Automatically load target sequence\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
If you find yourself working with the same target sequence each time you use \cf3 Amplify\cf0 , you can set that sequence to be loaded automatically.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Allow live scrolling of target sequence\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 Checking this box causes the target sequence to scroll actively as you move the scroll bar. If you computer is old and slow it might be better to deactivate this feature.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Preferred monospaced font\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 The Target Sequence window, the Primer List window, and the Results window require a monospaced font. You can enter the name of your favorite monospaced font here.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Sequence Header Boundary and header color\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
You can indicate a string of characters, such as "End Header" or ".." to mark the end of the header information in your target sequence files. When the target sequence is formatted, the header will be marked with the color shown here.\

\f0\b\fs40 Amplification Map\

\f1\b0\fs32 \
This map shows you what \cf3 Amplify\cf0  thinks is a likely outcome of your PCR. Sites along the target sequence where primers match are shown as rightward or leftward arrowheads above or below the line representing the target sequence. Amplified fragments ("amplicons") are shown below the matches.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 "Quality" of matches and amplicons\
\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 The size and boldness of the arrowheads and lines indicate how strongly those items are likely to appear in your amplification. In the case of the matches, the "quality" is only a function of the Primability and Stability calculated for that match. For the amplicons, it is determined by the quality of the corresponding primer matches as well as the length of the amplicon. Longer fragments amplify less well, and are therefore drawn with less emphasis. Amplicons are ordered with the strongest ones on top.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 When you pass the cursor over a map object\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
Placing your cursor over a match causes that match to be highlighted along with any amplicons for which that match was used. In addition, a line of text near the top of the map gives the full name of the primer and the position within the target sequence. \
\
When your cursor lies over an amplicon, that amplicon's line is highlighted along with the corresponding two primer matches. There is also a line of text near the top of the map indicating the names of the primers and the sizes of the amplicon's components. For "linear" fragments, the components consist of the left primer, the synthesized DNA and the right primer. The "circular" amplicons are indicated by arrowheads at the left and right ends of the line (to suggest continuation) as well as an interruption in the line. For those amplicons, the components are the rightward primer, the synthesized portion on the right end of the map, the synthesized portion on the left side of the map, and the leftward primer.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 When you click on a Match\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
When a match or amplicon is highlighted, you can click to obtain more detailed information. In addition, the portion of the target sequence corresponding to the match is selected. (You must open the Target Sequence window in order to see this selection.)\
\
For matches, Amplify shows you a diagram of how the primer and target sequence line up. For example:\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri-19445

\f3\fs28 \cf0 TGTCGGAAATTATGCGAACAGGAATTCTGGATAAACCCAAAAGGCTCCCATT\
                    ||||||||:  ||||||||\
                 3' CCTTAAGAYKCATTTGGGT 5'\
                    |                 |\
                 1719                1737\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri-19445

\f1\fs32 \cf0 \
We see that the primer matches the target sequence in the leftward direction between target positions 1719 and 1737. Furthermore, we can see that there are only two outright mismatches and one ambiguous match. All other sites match, as indicated by a vertical line.\
\
All sequence are drawn 5' to 3' unless otherwise indicated. Rightward matches are drawn like this:\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri-19445

\f3\fs28 \cf0                  2108                 2127\
                    |                  |\
                 5' ACCTTATMTTATTTCATCAT 3'\
                     | || |:|||||| |||||\
TGTCTTTTATCTGTTTCTTTTCATTTTATTATTTAATCATTATCCTTTTGCTT\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri-19445

\f1\fs32 \cf0 \
Note that since both the target and primer are shown 5' to 3', a match is actually a pair of identical rather than complementary bases. Drawing the two kinds of matches differently is done so that (a) the target sequence can always be shown 5' to 3', and (b) the primers can always be shown with their actual bases.\
\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri-19445

\f4\fs28 \cf2 \uc0\u55357 \u56633 
\f0\b   When you click on an amplicon\
\pard\tx6480\pardeftab720\ri-19445

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
When an amplicon is highlighted, you can click on it to see more detailed information about it. The "quality" of the amplicon is its length multiplied by the square of the product of the two match qualities. This is the measure used to arrange the amplicons in order on the map.\
\
Also shown is the sequence of the amplicon. Note that this sequence is not necessarily the same as the corresponding segment of the target sequence, because the two primers might not match perfectly.\
\
Finally, if you open the target sequence window after clicking on an amplicon, you will find the relevant portion of the sequence selected.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Ways of viewing the Amplification Map\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
Use the magnifying glass icon to expand the map around a particular point. The sizes of the match arrows will not increase, however. This feature allows you to distinguish between two matches that happen to lie very close together.\
\
You can also use the magnifying glass icon to reduce the size of the map by holding down the option key.\
\
Change the position of the map on your screen with the scroll bar and the grabber icon.\
\
The "Standard View" button restores the map to its normal size and position.\
\

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Saving and printing the map\

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf0 \
When you select "Save As ..." you create a file with a vector graphics version of your amplification map. The resulting file can be opened by most graphics software that support vector graphics. However, some programs do not recognize rotated text. In that case, the vertical primer names will not be visible.\
\
You can print a copy of the map to most printers. \
